### Frontend Code Implementation Guidelines
Follow these rules when you write code:
- Use early returns whenever possible to make the code more readable.
- Always use Tailwind classes for styling HTML elements; avoid using CSS or tags.
- Use “class:” instead of the tertiary operator in class tags whenever possible.
- Use descriptive variable and function/const names. Also, event functions should be named with a “handle” prefix, like “handleClick” for onClick and “handleKeyDown” for onKeyDown.
- Implement accessibility features on elements. For example, a tag should have a tabindex=“0”, aria-label, on:click, and on:keydown, and similar attributes.
- Use consts instead of functions, for example, “const toggle = () =>”. Also, define a type if possible.

### Backend Development (Laravel & PHP)
You are proficient in Laravel and PHP and will assist the user with backend-related tasks only when explicitly requested. If a task seems like it might require backend work, you may ask the user for confirmation before proceeding.

1. Code Structure & Best Practices
- Follow MVC principles—keep controllers thin and move business logic to services or repositories.
- Use dependency injection instead of making static calls inside classes.
- Avoid placing complex logic in controllers—delegate to service classes.
- Use Laravel Jobs/Queues for background tasks instead of handling everything in controllers.

2. Database Handling (Eloquent & Query Best Practices)
- Prefer Eloquent ORM over raw SQL for readability and maintainability.
- Use Eager Loading (with()) to reduce N+1 query issues.
- Utilize database transactions (DB::transaction) for atomic operations that modify multiple tables.
- Use model mutators & accessors for computed attributes instead of modifying values manually.
- Migrate databases using php artisan migrate, and avoid modifying the database manually.

3. API Development & Authentication
- Use Laravel Sanctum or Passport for authentication instead of manually handling tokens.
- Validate all incoming requests using FormRequest classes instead of manually writing validation logic.
- Implement rate limiting (throttle:60,1) on API endpoints to prevent abuse.
- Always return JSON responses for API endpoints (return response()->json([...])).
- Use API Resource classes (Resource::collection()) to format API responses consistently.

4. Security Best Practices
- Sanitize user input to prevent SQL injection & XSS.
- Use hashed passwords (Hash::make()) instead of storing plaintext passwords.
- Implement CSRF protection where necessary (Laravel does this by default for forms).
- Restrict access to admin routes using middleware (auth, can:admin).
- Log security-sensitive actions like login attempts and password changes.

5. Debugging & Testing
- Use Laravel Tinker (php artisan tinker) for quick debugging instead of dumping values in controllers.
- Use Log::debug() instead of dd() for production debugging.
- Write unit and feature tests using Laravel’s PHPUnit testing framework.
- Test API responses using Laravel’s built-in API testing tools ($this->json()).
- Implement Laravel Telescope for monitoring queries, logs, and debugging issues in development.

6. Performance Optimization
- Use Laravel caching (Cache::remember()) to store frequently accessed data.
- Optimize database queries using indexes and avoid unnecessary joins.
- Use Redis for caching and session storage in high-performance applications.
- Minimize database queries by batching inserts and using chunk() for large dataset processing.

